<article>
    <h1>Gla&#xAD;di&#xAD;a&#xAD;tor shakes up SUV arena</h1>
    <h2>Gi&#xAD;ant Jeep boasts un&#xAD;matched rugged&#xAD;ness, util&#xAD;ity and value</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200919/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-19"><time>2020-09-19</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MOTORING</span>
        - <span role="byline">Christo&#xAD;pher Tan Se&#xAD;nior Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent&#xD;&#xA;chris&#xAD;tan@sph.com.sg &#x2022;&#xD;&#xA;Fol&#xAD;low Christo&#xAD;pher Tan on In&#xAD;sta&#xAD;gram @chris.motoring</span>
    </section>

    <p>Jeep could have named its latest model Go­liath. At 5,591mm long, 1,894mm wide and 1,843mm tall, the new Gla­di­a­tor truck is mas­sive.</p>
    <p>Its length makes par­al­lel park­ing im­pos­si­ble, un­less you chance upon the first or last space.</p>
    <p>Within its length lies an equally ex­tra­or­di­nary wheel­base of 3,488mm. This means the Gla­di­a­tor has space for a twin-cabin as well as a 1.5m-long flatbed for cargo. But it also means the Jeep will not be able to ne­go­ti­ate many carpark ramps with­out climb­ing over some curbs. For­tu­nately, it is fit­ted with high-pro­file multi-ter­rain tyres, so there is no dan­ger of dam­ag­ing the wheels.</p>
    <p>Its long wheel­base makes for a cushy ride (for a truck), but it also means un­wieldy han­dling. Com­bined with its lad­der frame con­struc­tion – an ex­tended ver­sion of the Jeep Wran­gler’s – it makes for plenty of steering cor­rec­tion, even on straights. Hence it is not un­like the Suzuki Jimny or the MercedesBe­nz G-wagon, two other tra­di­tional off-road­ers.</p>
    <p>In com­par­i­son with the new Land Rover De­fender, which has a mono­coque con­struc­tion, the Gla­di­a­tor is a bit like a bull in a china shop.</p>
    <p>But hu­mans adapt. Af­ter a day of driv­ing the Gla­di­a­tor, you get ac­cus­tomed to its ways. It is still not as sharp and co­her­ent as a De­fender, but you get used to it – as long as you avoid tight U-turns.</p>
    <p>It is quite man­age­able at 70kmh – its max­i­mum speed as it can be reg­is­tered only as a com­mer­cial ve­hi­cle. For folks who do not mind this, the Gla­di­a­tor is a cool, unique ve­hi­cle which packs more util­ity than any sport util­ity ve­hi­cle here.</p>
    <p>And un­like the su­per tall De­fender, it can en­ter most cov­ered carparks here. It still has a fairly high ground clear­ance, so its side­steps are use­ful. Your perch is still pretty high, so you im­me­di­ately feel spe­cial be­hind the wheel.</p>
    <p>The Gla­di­a­tor’s tough-as-nails exterior – with re­move­able doors and roof (like the Wran­gler) – is trans­lated in­side the ve­hi­cle. Ev­ery­thing you see and touch is ro­bust</p>
    <p>and func­tional, such as all-weather rub­ber floor mats made for muddy boots. A sim­i­lar pro­tec­tion is avail­able for the cargo bed.</p>
    <p>A tough can­vas cover keeps mois­ture and pry­ing eyes out. Rolling the cover up frees up enough space for two scram­bler mo­tor­bikes (with tail­gate flipped down). Four moun­tain bi­cy­cles or a cou­ple of ca­noes should not be a prob­lem, ei­ther.</p>
    <p>Front and rear cam­eras, blindspot alerts and cruise con­trol en­hance the Gla­di­a­tor’s drive­abil­ity in town. An 8.4-inch in­fo­tain­ment sys­tem with nav­i­ga­tion en­sures you are never lost in the ur­ban jun­gle.</p>
    <p>Un­ex­pect­edly, this mam­moth four-wheel-drive is thirsty. Even though Jeep de­clares an econ­omy of 10.8 litres/100km, the Gla­di­a­tor’s ac­tual re­turn dur­ing this test­drive is al­most dou­ble that.</p>
    <p>Its low an­nual road tax ($596 ver­sus $3,330 for an equiv­a­lent pas­sen­ger-reg­is­tered ve­hi­cle) makes up for this. And for its price, no car can match its dol­lar­size ra­tio.</p>

